{"cursor":"8042","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Paul Ãmile de Puydt' (6 March 1810– 20 May 1891), a writer whose\ncontributions included work in botany and economics, was born and died in Mons,\nBelgium. His father name was Jean Ambroise de Puydt (1758â1836), who was\ngovernor of the Province Hainaut in the early days of Belgium from 1830 till\n1834. In the first marriage of his father there were 6 children. The famous Remi\nde Puydt came from this first marriage. He is a half brother of Paul Emile de\nPuydt. Remi de Puydtwas a civil engineer, a politician (representative) and\nserved in the Belgian army as\ncolonel. http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remi_De_Puydt and\nhttp://www.unionisme.be/De_Puydt.htm\n\nPaul-Emile was the second child of four children out of the second marriage of\nhis father Jean Ambroise de PUYDT (1758â1836), who married in 1799 with Marie\nAdÃ©laÃ¯de Jeanne MICHOT (ca 1777-1858). J-F. de Montigny, Tijschrift van de\nAntwerpse kring voor familiekunde, Jaargang IX, 1954, p100-115 As a\nbotanist, Paul Ãmile de Puydt notably wrote on\norchids. [http://www.antiquariaatjunk.com/item.php?item=3479 Les OrchidÃ©es],\nP.E. de Puydt The standard botanical author abbreviation 'De Puydt' is\napplied to species he described.\n\nAfter his study, he turned to journalism and worked as an editor of\n\"LâObsevateur du Hainaut\". Together with Henri-Florent Delmotte and Hippolyte\nRousselle, he wrote in 1831, the year where the current Belgium became separated\nfrom the northern Netherlands the theater piece \"Le candidat Ã  la royautÃ©:\nesquisse en trois tableaux mÃªlÃ©s de coupletsâ. This piece was played in Mons in\n1831. He then participated in the government, and he was also director of the\nMont-de-piÃ©tÃ© (Mount of piety) of Mons. J-F. de Montigny, Tijschrift van de\nAntwerpse kring voor familiekunde, Jaargang IX, 1954, p100-115 In his free\ntime he was interested in botany, and he developed a pronounced interest in\norchids. Since 1831 he was secretary of the founded societÃ© d'horticulture de\nMons. In 1833 he worked on the foundation of the SocietÃ© de arts et des lettres\ndu Hainaut, where he was vice-president and from 1865 president.\n\nAs a political economist, he is known as inventor of the concept of people\nhaving the freedom to choose which government to join, and governments having to\ncompete for citizens. He has given the name '[[panarchy]]' to this concept. His\npaper \"PANARCHIE\", P. E. de Puydt,\n[http://www.panarchy.org/depuydt/1860.eng.html Panarchy] was first\npublished in French in the Revue Trimestrielle, in Brussels, July 1860.\nPanarchie and its author Paul Emile de Puydt was only recently\nrediscovered Gian Piero de Bellis,\n[http://www.panarchy.org/debellis/depuydt.html Discovering de Puydt] The\nnotion of competitive government, but then limited to defense, can also be found\nin the writings of the Belgian economist Gustave de Molinari from 1849, eleven\nyears before de Puydt. Gustave de Molinari,\n[http://www.panarchy.org/molinari/security.html On the Production of\nSecurity] David Hart of the Department of History of Stanford University\nsuggests that Paul-Emile de Puydt might have been influenced by the works of his\nfellow countryman Gustave de Molinari. David M. Hart,\n[http://mises.org/journals/jls/6_1/6_1_5.pdf Gustave de Molinari and the Anti-\nstatist Liberal Tradition Part III, Journal of Libertarian Studies, Vol VI, no\n1, pages 86 to 88]\n\nHis work as a botanist is highly respected. Some of his books and novels had\nseveral editions.\n","linknr":175,"url":"Paul_Ãmile_de_Puydt","recorded":1376425455,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Paul_%C3%89mile_de_Puydt&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Paul_%C3%89mile_de_Puydt&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.